  <h1>Common Retaliation Claim Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m at-will so I can&rsquo;t sue for retaliation.&rdquo;</h2><p>At-will employment means an employer can terminate for any reason or no reason — but not for an illegal reason. Retaliating against an employee for protected activity is illegal under numerous federal and state statutes regardless of at-will status. At-will is a default rule, not a blanket immunity.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I have to be fired to have a retaliation claim.&rdquo;</h2><p>No. <em>Burlington Northern</em> (2006) expanded retaliation to cover any materially adverse action — including demotions, pay cuts, negative reviews, and hostile treatment — that would deter a reasonable employee from engaging in protected activity.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;My underlying discrimination claim has to succeed for retaliation to matter.&rdquo;</h2><p>Retaliation is an independent claim. You can have a strong retaliation claim even if the underlying discrimination claim is weak or fails. Courts routinely find retaliation liability without finding liability on the original discrimination claim.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I complained informally, so it doesn&rsquo;t count.&rdquo;</h2><p>Informal internal complaints are protected activity under Title VII. You do not need to file a formal EEOC charge first to get protection against retaliation. Even a verbal complaint to HR is sufficient.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Too much time has passed.&rdquo;</h2><p>The EEOC charge deadline (180/300 days) controls whether you can bring a federal claim. If that deadline has passed, consult an attorney about state law claims, which often have longer statutes of limitations.</p>
